    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_166041655" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/166041655" />
    <a title="AppleJuice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/393458-applejuice"><img alt="AppleJuice" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/166041655?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="AppleJuice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="AppleJuice" href="/user/show/393458-applejuice">AppleJuice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer166041655" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6619686739539294545">A book written with a very light touch and total lack of melodrama, which is the ideal approach when writing about people whose lives were tragically affected by the Holocaust. Father Anselm is an English monk whose peaceful life of prayer is disrupted when a recently-exposed Nazi war criminal seeks Sanctuary in his monastery.<br/><br/>Lucy is the grand-daughter of a French woman, Agnes, who refuses to speak of her experiences in war-time Paris and subsequent internment in Auschwitz. Agnes is diagnosed wi</span>
  <span id="freeText6619686739539294545" style="display:none">A book written with a very light touch and total lack of melodrama, which is the ideal approach when writing about people whose lives were tragically affected by the Holocaust. Father Anselm is an English monk whose peaceful life of prayer is disrupted when a recently-exposed Nazi war criminal seeks Sanctuary in his monastery.<br /><br />Lucy is the grand-daughter of a French woman, Agnes, who refuses to speak of her experiences in war-time Paris and subsequent internment in Auschwitz. Agnes is diagnosed with a terminal illness and knows that it's now or never to tell her heartbreaking tale to Lucy, with whom she has a close relationship. She feels she failed Lucy's father, her son... Anges' story is told in parallel with Father Anslem's investigations into what the alleged Nazi did in the war, and why the Church assisted his escape to Britain. <br /><br />It sounds like a heavy story, but the delicacy of the language chosen allows the reader to absorb the events by gentle osmosis. The contrast of the monk's life of retreat, ritualised silence and lack of family relations, (of all kinds), with the passions and violence of life "outside" was done with subtlety and elegance.<br /><br />Overall, a book that has a welcomely calm feel, and is wonderfully uncluttered with the purple prose and unnecessary editorialising of characters' thoughts which have ruined several great stories I have recently read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6619686739539294545" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

